Table 1 also shows that ai-vpfit required an increasing number of components as the knot spacing increases, the largest number being required when ai-vpfit was supplied with the original continuum. This trend is unsurprising because as the knot spacing is increased, the spline model tends to the (coarser) original continuum. Table 1 also shows that ai-vpfit required an increasing number of components as the knot spacing increases, the largest number being required when ai-vpfit was supplied with the original continuum. This trend is unsurprising because as the knot spacing is increased, the spline model tends to the (coarser) original continuum. The variation in the number of components does not indicate a preference for any particular continuum, but it does provide independent evidence that there is a source of uncertainty associated with continuum modelling that must be taken into account in the overall <math alttext="\Delta\alpha/\alpha" class="ltx_Math" display="inline" id="S5.SS2.p2.1.m1.1">

references: To investigate the source of the effects described in the preceding paragraph, we carried out an additional set of 120 ai-vpfit calculations, with continuum refinement, in which the initial continua for 5 (out of of 6) spectral segments were the original ones, whilst the continuum for one remaining spectral segment at a time was replaced with the locally refined continuum. This was done for one specific knot spacing only (5Å, because calculation times are fairly long). The results from these 120 new models are given in Table 5, which show the strongest impact arises when the Fe ii 1608Å continuum is replaced, suggesting the difference between the original and refined continua plays an more important role in this wavelength region (see Fig.1). Interestingly, Si ii 1808Å also displays a similarly large offset but this appears not to impact substantially in this case.
